outputs.output:
{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Checking the weather app before heading out? That 70% chance of rain is probability at work. You grab an umbrella not because it will definitely rain, but because the odds are high enough to justify a small inconvenience.",
      "title": "Checking the Weather App"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every time you swipe right or left, dating apps use probability behind the scenes to predict compatibility. But you do it too — mentally estimating the chances of a good match based on photos, bios, and shared interests.",
      "title": "Swiping on Dating Apps"
    },
    {
      "text": "Poker players live and breathe probability. Deciding whether to go all-in isn't just gut feeling — it's calculating the odds of completing a flush or straight based on the cards still unseen.",
      "title": "Game Night Poker Hands"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your car insurance premium is literally a probability calculation. Insurers estimate the likelihood you'll file a claim based on your age, driving history, and location, then price accordingly.",
      "title": "Your Insurance Premium"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a basketball commentator says a player shoots 45% from three-point range, that's probability telling the coach whether to design a play around that shooter in crunch time.",
      "title": "Sports Commentary Stats"
    },
    {
      "text": "Should you leave 10 minutes early or risk the usual route? You're unconsciously weighing the probability of traffic, red lights, and delays — running a mental simulation every morning.",
      "title": "Your Morning Commute Gamble"
    },
    {
      "text": "A doctor says a treatment has a 90% success rate. That single number shapes whether you proceed, seek a second opinion, or explore alternatives. Medical decisions lean heavily on probability thinking.",
      "title": "At the Doctor's Office"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spotify's Discover Weekly feels like magic, but it's probability — estimating the likelihood you'll enjoy a song based on what millions of similar listeners also loved.",
      "title": "Spotify's Song Suggestions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Investors diversify portfolios because putting everything in one stock means the probability of a big loss is uncomfortably high. Spreading bets is probability thinking applied to money.",
      "title": "Investing Your Savings"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you grab a bag of chips from a vending machine and wonder if it'll get stuck, you're doing probability. It happened twice last month — maybe it's time to pick a different row.",
      "title": "The Vending Machine Gamble"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ever notice how Uber charges more on a rainy Friday night? Tons of people request rides (demand spikes) while fewer drivers are out. The app's surge pricing is supply and demand adjusting in real time, right on your phone.",
      "title": "Surge Pricing on a Rainy Night"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a new console drops and stores sell out in minutes, resellers list them at double the price. Limited supply meets massive demand, and suddenly a $500 system is going for $1,000 on eBay.",
      "title": "Console Launch Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strawberries in summer? Cheap and everywhere. In January, fewer farms can grow them, so supply shrinks and prices climb. Your grocery bill quietly reflects which crops are in season and which aren't.",
      "title": "Seasonal Produce Prices"
    },
    {
      "text": "When Taylor Swift announces a stadium tour, millions compete for limited seats. Ticket prices soar because demand wildly exceeds supply — that's why you see $800 nosebleed seats on resale sites.",
      "title": "Concert Ticket Frenzy"
    },
    {
      "text": "Real estate agents know this well. When a hot neighborhood has few homes listed but dozens of buyers competing, bidding wars push prices way above asking. More inventory? Prices cool off.",
      "title": "The Housing Market Bidding War"
    },
    {
      "text": "Airlines constantly adjust fares. Book a Tuesday flight months ahead and it's affordable. Wait until the day before a busy holiday, and that same seat costs three times more — fewer seats left, more travelers desperate to fly.",
      "title": "Airline Ticket Timing"
    },
    {
      "text": "During a hiring boom in tech, companies compete for scarce developers by offering higher salaries and perks. When layoffs flood the market with talent, employers can offer less. Your paycheck is shaped by supply and demand too.",
      "title": "Your Salary at Work"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remember the 2020 toilet paper shortage? Demand exploded overnight while supply chains couldn't keep up. Shelves emptied, and some sellers charged outrageous prices — a textbook supply-demand mismatch playing out in real time.",
      "title": "The Toilet Paper Panic"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vintage sneaker collectors watch supply and demand obsessively. A limited Jordan release with only 5,000 pairs? Prices skyrocket. A general release restocked three times? The resale value barely budges.",
      "title": "Sneaker Resale Culture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Farmers' markets on a Sunday afternoon often have vendors slashing prices on leftover produce. Supply still exists but demand is fading as the market closes — so prices drop to move what's left.",
      "title": "End-of-Day Market Deals"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open any folder on your computer and there's another folder inside. Open that one — more folders. Your entire file system is a recursive structure: folders within folders within folders, each level looking exactly like the one above it.",
      "title": "Folders Inside Folders"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand between two mirrors facing each other and you see yourself reflected into infinity — a reflection of a reflection of a reflection. Barbershops, elevators with mirrored walls, even dressing rooms create this visual recursion naturally.",
      "title": "Mirrors Facing Each Other"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those Russian nesting dolls — matryoshkas — are recursion you can hold. Open one and find a smaller identical doll inside. Open that one, same thing. Until you reach the tiniest doll that doesn't open. That's your base case, right in your hands.",
      "title": "Russian Nesting Dolls"
    },
    {
      "text": "GPS apps find the shortest route by breaking your trip into smaller segments. \"What's the best path from A to Z?\" becomes \"What's the best path from A to B, then B to Z?\" — each piece splitting further until the answer is trivial.",
      "title": "GPS Route Finding"
    },
    {
      "text": "Zoom into a fern leaf and notice each branch looks like a miniature copy of the whole fern. Romanesco broccoli, snowflakes, river deltas, lightning bolts — nature builds stunning complexity by repeating a simple pattern at every scale.",
      "title": "Fractals in Nature"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ever Googled the word \"recursion\"? Google shows \"Did you mean: recursion\" — linking right back to the same search. It's a famous Easter egg that perfectly demonstrates self-reference with a wink.",
      "title": "Google's Easter Egg"
    },
    {
      "text": "Customer support transfers you to another department, who transfers you again, who transfers you... until finally someone actually answers your question. That final person who resolves it without transferring? They're the base case.",
      "title": "The Call Center Loop"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the movie Inception, characters enter dreams within dreams within dreams — each layer a smaller, self-similar world. They need to resolve each level from the deepest up, just like recursive calls returning their results back up the chain.",
      "title": "Inception's Dream Layers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Corporate org charts are recursive. A CEO manages VPs, each VP manages directors, each director manages teams. \"Who reports to whom?\" at any level looks structurally identical to every other level, just at a different scale.",
      "title": "Company Org Charts"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you sort a messy deck of cards by splitting it in half, sorting each half, then merging them back — that's merge sort. Each half gets split again and again until you're comparing just two cards. Recursion makes the chaos manageable.",
      "title": "Sorting a Deck of Cards"
    },
    {
      "text": "Family trees are inherently recursive. Your ancestors are your parents plus their ancestors. Genealogy software traces lineages by recursively following parent links until it hits someone with no recorded parents — the base case of your history.",
      "title": "Tracing Your Family Tree"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Você entra no shopping só pra \"dar uma olhada\" e sai com uma blusa que estava com 70% de desconto. O preço original era R$300, mas pagou R$90. Parece um achado, né? Mas você nem precisava de uma blusa. O preço âncora de R$300 fez R$90 parecer irresistível.",
      "title": "A \"promoção imperdível\" no shopping"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você vai votar e já decidiu seu candidato. No debate, ele fala bobagem e o adversário apresenta bons argumentos. Mesmo assim, você sai pensando \"meu candidato foi melhor\". Sem perceber, você filtrou tudo pelo que já acreditava antes de sentar no sofá.",
      "title": "Na hora de votar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquele casal que briga toda semana, mas ninguém termina. Já investiram 5 anos juntos e sentem que \"não podem jogar tudo fora\". O tempo investido vira uma âncora emocional que impede de avaliar se o relacionamento faz sentido agora.",
      "title": "O relacionamento que não acaba"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu time perde 3 jogos seguidos e você diz \"agora VAI ganhar, é a lei das probabilidades\". Isso é a falácia do jogador — achar que eventos passados influenciam resultados independentes. Cada jogo é um jogo novo, mas o cérebro insiste em ver padrões.",
      "title": "Apostando no jogo do seu time"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você abre o app de delivery e vê que um restaurante tem 4.8 estrelas com 2.000 avaliações. Outro tem comida que te atrai mais, mas só 4.2 estrelas. Você escolhe o 4.8 — seguindo a multidão sem questionar se os critérios dos outros são os seus.",
      "title": "Escolhendo no delivery"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na reunião, o chefe propõe uma ideia. Você discorda, mas vê todos concordando. Quando chega sua vez, você também concorda. A pressão do grupo não mudou sua opinião — mudou seu comportamento, e depois sua mente se ajusta pra justificar.",
      "title": "Na reunião de trabalho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você lê uma notícia sobre queda de avião e fica com medo de voar na viagem de férias. Mas dirige tranquilamente todo dia — algo estatisticamente muito mais perigoso. Eventos dramáticos ficam mais \"disponíveis\" na memória e distorcem sua percepção de risco.",
      "title": "O medo de avião"
    },
    {
      "text": "Médicos experientes podem diagnosticar rápido demais porque o primeiro sintoma lembra um caso anterior. Investidores mantêm ações em queda porque \"já caiu demais, tem que subir\". Até profissionais treinados caem nos mesmos atalhos mentais que todo mundo.",
      "title": "Profissionais também caem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você segue perfis de fitness no Instagram e começa a achar que todo mundo malha e come saudável. Sua percepção da \"normalidade\" é distorcida pela bolha do algoritmo, que te mostra mais do que você já consome — reforçando uma realidade editada.",
      "title": "Seu feed nas redes sociais"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cada invierno, los médicos recomiendan una nueva vacuna contra la gripe. ¿Por qué? Porque el virus muta constantemente y las cepas que evaden nuestras defensas se propagan más. Es selección natural en tiempo real, obligándonos a actualizar vacunas cada temporada.",
      "title": "La vacuna de la gripe que cambia cada año"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando un doctor te dice \"termina todo el antibiótico\", no es capricho. Si cortas el tratamiento, las bacterias más resistentes sobreviven y se multiplican. Los superbichos hospitalarios como el MRSA son selección natural acelerada por nuestro propio descuido.",
      "title": "Bacterias resistentes en el hospital"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los perros chihuahuas y los gran daneses comparten ancestro: el lobo. Durante miles de años, los humanos eligieron qué perros se reproducían según rasgos deseados. Es selección natural dirigida por nosotros, llamada selección artificial, y la ves cada vez que paseas a tu mascota.",
      "title": "Tu perro es evidencia viviente"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las polillas en la Inglaterra industrial se oscurecieron cuando el hollín cubrió los árboles. Las claras eran presa fácil y las oscuras se camuflaban mejor. Cuando el aire se limpió, las claras regresaron. Es un caso de libro que puedes ver en cualquier documental de naturaleza.",
      "title": "Polillas que cambian de color"
    },
    {
      "text": "¿Notaste que las plagas del jardín siempre vuelven aunque fumigues? Los insectos que toleran el pesticida sobreviven y sus hijos heredan esa tolerancia. Por eso los agricultores rotan productos constantemente: están en una carrera armamentista con la selección natural.",
      "title": "Plagas de jardín que no mueren"
    },
    {
      "text": "En juegos como Pokémon o Spore, eliges qué criaturas evolucionan según sus rasgos. Los desarrolladores se inspiraron directamente en la selección natural: los más aptos avanzan, los demás se quedan atrás. Ahora sabes que esa mecánica tiene base biológica real.",
      "title": "Evolución en los videojuegos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los peces de colores brillantes en un arrecife no son solo bonitos: esos colores señalan salud y buenos genes a las hembras. Los machos más llamativos se reproducen más. La próxima vez que veas un documental marino, recuerda que esos colores son resultado de generaciones de selección.",
      "title": "Colores llamativos en el arrecife"
    },
    {
      "text": "El plátano que comes casi no tiene semillas porque los agricultores seleccionaron las plantas con menos. Pero esa falta de diversidad genética los hace vulnerables a hongos. La selección humana los hizo deliciosos, pero la naturaleza podría cobrar la factura.",
      "title": "El plátano del supermercado"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When Netflix suggests a show you end up binging, that's a model trained on millions of viewing habits spotting patterns in what you watch, when you pause, and what you skip. It's quietly predicting your next obsession.",
      "title": "Your Netflix Recommendations"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type \"hap\" and your phone offers \"happy birthday!\" — a model trained on billions of text messages predicts what you'll say next. It even adapts to your quirky slang over time.",
      "title": "Phone Keyboard Predictions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ever notice Gmail drafting the end of your sentence in gray text? A model trained on email patterns predicts how you'll finish phrases like \"Let me know if you have any...\" — and it's often spot on.",
      "title": "Smart Compose in Email"
    },
    {
      "text": "Upload a group selfie and Facebook or Google Photos instantly knows who's who. Models trained on facial features can distinguish your friends even in tricky lighting or weird angles.",
      "title": "Photo Tagging Your Friends"
    },
    {
      "text": "Say \"Hey Siri\" or \"OK Google\" and your assistant understands you despite your accent, background noise, or mumbling. Models trained on countless voice samples decode your speech in real time.",
      "title": "Voice Assistants Listening"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spotify's Discover Weekly playlist feels like a friend who just gets your taste. A model analyzes your listening history alongside millions of other users to surface songs you've never heard but will probably love.",
      "title": "Spotify's Weekly Playlist"
    },
    {
      "text": "Before a fraudulent charge even reaches you, your bank's models have scanned the transaction — comparing it against your normal spending patterns — and flagged it as suspicious in milliseconds.",
      "title": "Credit Card Fraud Alerts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Google Maps doesn't just show the fastest route right now. Models trained on years of traffic data predict where congestion will build 20 minutes from now and reroute you preemptively.",
      "title": "Traffic Predictions on Maps"
    },
    {
      "text": "TikTok's For You page is famously addictive because its model learns your preferences incredibly fast — tracking not just likes but how long you watch each clip before scrolling.",
      "title": "TikTok's For You Page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your email's spam filter has seen billions of junk messages. It catches phishing attempts and scam offers before you ever see them, constantly retraining as spammers invent new tricks.",
      "title": "Spam Filters at Work"
    },
    {
      "text": "Doctors use models trained on thousands of X-rays and scans to catch tumors or fractures that human eyes might miss. ML is becoming a second opinion in radiology departments worldwide.",
      "title": "Medical Scans at the Hospital"
    },
    {
      "text": "Online shops show you \"customers also bought\" suggestions. Behind that is a model connecting purchase patterns across millions of shoppers to predict what you might want to add to your cart.",
      "title": "Shopping Recommendations"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "That $1,000 your grandma put in a savings account when you were born? By the time you're 30, it could be worth over $3,000 without anyone adding a penny. The money just kept growing on itself quietly in the background while you were busy growing up.",
      "title": "The Birthday Gift That Grew Itself"
    },
    {
      "text": "Credit card debt is compounding working against you. Carry a $5,000 balance at 24% and make only minimums — years later you've paid thousands in interest on interest. The same force that builds wealth can trap you in a debt spiral.",
      "title": "Credit Card Debt Snowball"
    },
    {
      "text": "Followers, views, shares — social media growth is compounding in action. A video gets shared, those people share it, and suddenly you're viral. Each wave of exposure multiplies the next, which is why growth feels slow then explosive.",
      "title": "Going Viral on Social Media"
    },
    {
      "text": "Invest $200/month starting at 22 and you could retire with far more than someone investing $400/month starting at 35. That head start doesn't just add more — it multiplies more. Time is compounding's secret ingredient.",
      "title": "Your 401(k) at Work"
    },
    {
      "text": "Practice guitar 20 minutes a day and progress feels invisible for weeks. Then suddenly you're playing full songs. Each skill builds on the last, accelerating what you can learn next. Compounding isn't just about money — it's how skills grow too.",
      "title": "Learning a Musical Instrument"
    },
    {
      "text": "Real estate investors know this well. A $300,000 home appreciating at 4% annually gains $12,000 the first year. But year ten? The gain is bigger because it's 4% of a much larger number. Property values compound just like bank accounts.",
      "title": "Your Home's Rising Value"
    },
    {
      "text": "A sourdough starter doubles in size every few hours under the right conditions. Bakers watch exponential growth happen on their countertop — what starts as a small blob overtakes the jar. Nature compounds too.",
      "title": "Sourdough on the Counter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Warren Buffett earned over 99% of his wealth after age 50. Not because he suddenly got smarter, but because decades of compounding finally hit their stride. Professionals call this the \"hockey stick\" moment.",
      "title": "Buffett's Billions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Reinvesting stock dividends is compounding on display. Buy 100 shares, dividends buy 3 more, those 103 shares earn bigger dividends, which buy even more shares. Your ownership quietly snowballs without you spending another dime.",
      "title": "Dividend Reinvestment Plans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fitness works this way too. Early workouts build a base, then each session builds on improved strength. A year in, the same effort produces way bigger results. Your body compounds the investment you make in it.",
      "title": "The Gym Gains Curve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Aquele ar fresco que você sente ao entrar num parque cheio de árvores? É fotossíntese em tempo real. As árvores ao redor estão absorvendo CO2 e liberando O2 enquanto você passeia. Cada respiração profunda ali é abastecida por esse processo.",
      "title": "Passeio no Parque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Arroz, feijão, frutas, legumes — tudo que está no seu prato começou com fotossíntese. A glicose gerada pelas plantas é a base de toda cadeia alimentar. Até a carne que você come veio de um animal que se alimentou de plantas.",
      "title": "Sua Refeição de Todo Dia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Florestas tropicais como a Amazônia funcionam como enormes filtros de carbono. A fotossíntese retira toneladas de CO2 da atmosfera, regulando o clima do planeta. Quando desmatamos, esse filtro encolhe e o aquecimento acelera.",
      "title": "Mudanças Climáticas no Jornal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Placas solares se inspiram na fotossíntese. Cientistas estudam como as plantas convertem luz em energia para criar tecnologias mais eficientes. A natureza já faz isso há bilhões de anos — nós tentamos copiar.",
      "title": "Energia Solar no Telhado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Algas microscópicas nos oceanos fazem fotossíntese e produzem mais da metade do oxigênio do planeta. Aquele documentário sobre vida marinha que você assistiu? O oceano respira por causa dessas criaturas invisíveis.",
      "title": "Documentários sobre o Oceano"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquário com plantas aquáticas? Elas fazem fotossíntese ali dentro, oxigenando a água pros peixes. Se a luz do aquário quebra, as plantas param de produzir O2 e os peixes podem sufocar.",
      "title": "Seu Aquário em Casa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Produtores de café, soja e trigo dependem diretamente da fotossíntese. Dias nublados demais reduzem a produção, afetando preços no supermercado. A economia agrícola do Brasil gira em torno desse processo celular.",
      "title": "Agronegócio e Preço no Mercado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em filmes de ficção científica como \"O Marciano\", cultivar plantas em Marte é questão de sobrevivência. Sem fotossíntese, não há comida nem oxigênio. A cena da estufa marciana mostra por que esse processo é insubstituível.",
      "title": "Sobrevivência em Marte no Cinema"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quem pratica jardinagem sabe: planta na sombra cresce fraca. Você escolhe o local mais ensolarado do jardim intuitivamente — na prática, está otimizando a fotossíntese das suas plantas sem perceber.",
      "title": "Jardinagem no Fim de Semana"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cuando envías un mensaje por WhatsApp o Signal, la encriptación de extremo a extremo lo protege. Ni la propia app puede leerlo — solo tú y la persona que lo recibe. Esas fotos, audios y textos viajan blindados sin que lo notes.",
      "title": "Tus chats de mensajería"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al pagar con tu tarjeta en una tienda online o usar Apple Pay en el supermercado, la encriptación protege tu número de tarjeta y datos bancarios. Por eso puedes comprar tranquilo sin que alguien intercepte tu información financiera.",
      "title": "Pagos y compras online"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu iPhone o Android encripta todo el contenido del dispositivo cuando lo bloqueas. Si alguien lo roba, no puede acceder a tus fotos, contactos ni apps aunque conecte el almacenamiento a otra computadora. Sin tu PIN, todo es ilegible.",
      "title": "Tu celular bloqueado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando Netflix o Spotify te muestran contenido, usan encriptación para proteger los derechos de autor. Las películas y canciones viajan encriptadas hasta tu dispositivo, evitando que alguien las copie directamente de la señal.",
      "title": "Streaming de películas y música"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gmail, Outlook y otros servicios encriptan tus correos mientras viajan por internet. Esa conversación con tu jefe, el recibo del banco o la confirmación de un vuelo — todo se mueve protegido entre servidores.",
      "title": "Tu correo electrónico"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando te conectas a la red Wi-Fi de tu casa con contraseña, esa conexión usa encriptación WPA. Sin ella, cualquier vecino podría ver qué páginas visitas o capturar tus contraseñas desde su propia computadora.",
      "title": "El Wi-Fi de tu casa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Google Drive, iCloud y Dropbox encriptan tus archivos almacenados en la nube. Esas fotos familiares y documentos de trabajo están protegidos incluso si alguien accediera a los servidores físicos donde se guardan.",
      "title": "Tus archivos en la nube"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al usar una VPN para trabajar remoto o navegar desde un café, todo tu tráfico de internet se encripta. Es como un túnel invisible — ni el dueño del café ni tu proveedor de internet pueden ver qué haces en línea.",
      "title": "VPN en el café"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las apps de tu banco usan múltiples capas de encriptación. Cada transferencia, consulta de saldo o pago de servicios viaja protegido. Por eso puedes mover dinero desde el sofá con la misma seguridad que en una sucursal.",
      "title": "Tu app bancaria"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando desbloqueas tu celular con huella o reconocimiento facial, esos datos biométricos se guardan encriptados en un chip especial del dispositivo. Ni siquiera el fabricante del teléfono puede acceder a tu huella digital.",
      "title": "Tu huella dactilar digital"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When a video goes viral on TikTok or YouTube, the algorithm shows it to more people because it's popular — which makes it even more popular. That snowballing view count is a positive feedback loop baked into every social media platform you use daily.",
      "title": "Viral Videos on Social Media"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your body temperature stays near 98.6°F because when you overheat, you sweat to cool down. When you're cold, you shiver to warm up. You're walking around with one of nature's most elegant negative feedback loops running 24/7.",
      "title": "Your Body's Built-In Thermostat"
    },
    {
      "text": "When people panic-buy toilet paper or gas, empty shelves make others panic more, which drives even more buying. This positive feedback loop turned minor supply hiccups into full-blown shortages during 2020.",
      "title": "Panic Buying at the Store"
    },
    {
      "text": "Skip the gym once and it's easier to skip again. But go three days in a row and momentum builds — you start wanting to go. Both directions are feedback loops shaping your habits without you noticing.",
      "title": "The Habit Spiral"
    },
    {
      "text": "In Civilization or SimCity, investing in education boosts your economy, which funds more education. Neglect it and poverty deepens, draining resources further. Strategy games are basically feedback loop simulators.",
      "title": "Strategy Games You Play"
    },
    {
      "text": "Arctic ice reflects sunlight. As warming melts ice, darker ocean absorbs more heat, which melts more ice. Climate scientists watch this positive feedback loop closely because it accelerates change faster than models predict.",
      "title": "Melting Ice and Rising Seas"
    },
